<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">

<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8" />
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
  <title><%= title %></title>
  <meta name="description" content="<%= description %>" />
  <link rel="icon" href="/favicon.svg" type="image/svg+xml" />
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/styles.css" />
</head>

<body>
  <main class="shell shell-wide">
    <section class="hero hero-compact">
      <h1><a class="hero-home" href="/"><%= serviceName %></a></h1>
      <span class="hero-connector" aria-hidden="true"></span>
      <nav class="top-menu" aria-label="Primary">
        <a href="/">Home</a>
        <span class="top-menu-separator" aria-hidden="true">|</span>
        <a href="/geofeeds" aria-current="page">Geofeeds</a>
        <span class="top-menu-separator" aria-hidden="true">|</span>
        <a href="/docs">Docs</a>
      </nav>
    </section>

    <section class="grid grid-single">
      <article class="panel panel-wide panel-copy-block">
        <h2>All Discovered Geofeeds - <%= geofeedCount.toLocaleString("en-US") %></h2>
        <p>
          The most complete public list of all discovered geofeed URLs, updated every 4 hours.
        </p>
        <div class="action-row">
          <a class="action-link" href="<%= csvUrl %>" download>Download geofeeds.csv</a>
          <a class="action-link" href="<%= jsonUrl %>" download>Download geofeeds.json</a>
        </div>
          <dl class="stats stats-grid">
              <div>
                  <dt>Last update - <%= latestSuccessAtLabel %></dt>
              </div>
          </dl>

      </article>

      <article class="panel panel-wide panel-copy-block">
        <h2>Geofeed Directory</h2>
        <p>
          This page is a public geofeed list and geofeed directory for people trying to find geofeeds in one place.
          If you need all discovered geofeeds, public geofeed URLs, or a complete geofeed list to review, this page
          brings those sources together in a single view.
        </p>
        <p>
          Geofeeds are published files that map IP address ranges to location data. You can use this list to browse
          geofeed URLs, review the latest successful fetch time for each entry, and spot recently validated geofeed
          sources for IP geolocation research, network operations, and data quality checks.
        </p>
        <p>
          For anyone looking for a downloadable geofeed list, the JSON dump provides a simple way to work with the
          latest geofeeds in scripts, automation, or offline analysis. If you are new to the format, read
          <a href="/what-is-geofeed">what a geofeed is</a>.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>
    <%- include("partials/footer.ejs") %>
  </main>
</body>

</html>
